attack SqlInjectionEcommerce {
    mitre_id   : "T1190" ;
    category   : APPLICATION ;
    difficulty : MEDIUM ;

    real_world_case {
        year        : 2021 ;
        victim      : "Hundreds of e-commerce platforms running on 
Magento, WooCommerce, and custom-built PHP/MySQL stacks; among the 
most significant documented SQL injection-related breaches of recent 
years, the 2021 Carding Mafia forum SQL injection and data breach 
exposed 297,000+ records and hashed creds; Peloton API SQL injection 
discovery in 2021 exposed customer PII; ClubHouse SQL injection 
exposed 3.8M user records in 2021; the broader Magecart ecosystem 
routinely uses SQL injection as the entry vector for web skimmer 
implantation on e-commerce platforms, with Group-IB estimating 
over 4,700 e-commerce websites compromised by Magecart skimmers 
at any single point in time between 2019-2022; in 2023 the 
MOVEit Transfer SQL injection (CVE-2023-34362) was exploited 
by the Cl0p ransomware group affecting 2,500+ organisations 
and 62M+ individuals" ;
        impact      : "Extraction of customer PII databases including 
names, email addresses, physical addresses, and order history; 
extraction of hashed or plaintext stored passwords enabling 
credential stuffing attacks against other services; in some 
cases extraction of stored partial or full payment card data; 
administrative access via extracted admin credentials enabling 
web skimmer implantation (Magecart-style) to capture payment 
data from live transactions; secondary impact through regulatory 
fines under GDPR (EU), PCI DSS penalties, and legal liability 
from affected customers; reputational damage and customer 
churn following public breach disclosure" ;
        attribution : "Magecart affiliated groups (primarily 
financially motivated criminal syndicate) targeting e-commerce 
platforms; individual criminal actors using automated SQLMap 
scanning; Cl0p ransomware group for the MOVEit CVE-2023-34362 
exploitation" ;
    }

    attack_vector : "SQL injection against e-commerce applications 
occurs wherever user-controlled input is incorporated into SQL 
query strings without parameterisation. In modern e-commerce 
platforms the attack surface includes: product search parameters, 
category and filter query strings, customer account login and 
registration forms, order lookup by ID or tracking number, 
coupon code validation, and API endpoint parameters. A classic 
error-based or UNION-based injection in a search parameter ('or 
1=1 -- appended to disrupt query logic) allows the attacker to 
probe database schema by inducing verbose error messages or 
inferring schema via boolean-blind or time-based blind techniques 
when error output is suppressed. Once table names, column names, 
and row counts are enumerated via information_schema queries, 
the attacker issues UNION SELECT queries to extract customer PII, 
credential hashes, payment tokens, and admin accounts from the 
database. Out-of-band exfiltration using DNS or HTTP requests 
triggered by database functions (xp_cmdshell on SQL Server, 
LOAD_FILE and INTO OUTFILE on MySQL with appropriate permissions, 
UTL_HTTP on Oracle) provides a covert extraction channel that 
bypasses many WAF inspections focused on in-band responses. 
File write capabilities on MySQL with misconfigured permissions 
allow writing a web shell to the web root, providing persistent 
command execution. Automated tools such as SQLMap dramatically 
reduce the skill required by automating parameter discovery, 
injection technique selection, and data extraction" ;

    target_profile : "E-commerce platforms built on PHP/MySQL stacks 
including Magento, WooCommerce, OpenCart, and custom-built stores; 
platforms with legacy codebases predating secure coding practices, 
third-party plugins adding injection-vulnerable query paths, 
or insufficient input validation in custom extension code; 
applications without a WAF or with a WAF bypass using encoding 
variations; platforms processing live payment card data as a 
very high-value target for skimmer implantation" ;

    success_rate        : 50-80% ;
    average_impact      : "Extraction of full customer database 
including PII for 10,000-10,000,000 customers depending on 
platform size; credential hash extraction for offline cracking; 
in Magecart scenarios: persistent payment skimmer generating 
live card data capture for the duration until discovery; 
average time-to-discovery for Magecart-style compromises is 
22 days based on RiskIQ research; regulatory fines for GDPR 
violations can reach 4% of annual global revenue" ;
    delivery_method     : "Automated parameter injection via SQLMap 
or similar tooling against exposed GET/POST parameters; manual 
targeted injection against specific high-value platform 
functionality; API endpoint injection via crafted JSON/XML 
body parameters bypassing query string WAF rules" ;
    detection_difficulty : MEDIUM ;

    prevention_measures : [
        "Exclusively use parameterised queries (prepared statements) 
or stored procedures for all database interactions in application 
code; ORM frameworks (Eloquent, Doctrine, Django ORM) are 
parameterised by default and should be preferred over raw 
query construction; never concatenate user input into SQL 
query strings regardless of prior validation steps",
        "Implement a web application firewall with SQL injection 
detection signatures in enforcement mode; deploy WAF rules 
covering UNION, information_schema, benchmark(), sleep(), 
and encoding-bypassed variants; review WAF bypass techniques 
quarterly and update signatures accordingly",
        "Apply principle of least privilege to database accounts: 
the application database account should have only SELECT, 
INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE on required tables — no FILE, 
EXECUTE, CREATE, or DROP privileges; configure MySQL 
to deny INTO OUTFILE and LOAD_FILE operations from 
the application account",
        "Implement comprehensive input validation at the application 
layer as a defence-in-depth measure (not a replacement for 
parameterisation): allowlist expected character sets for each 
input field, reject inputs containing SQL metacharacter sequences, 
and enforce length limits",
        "Conduct regular DAST (dynamic application security testing) 
using automated scanners and penetration testing against all 
input surfaces of the e-commerce platform, including API 
endpoints and custom plugin code, prior to production deployment 
and after significant codebase changes"
    ] ;

    cve_references : [
        "CVE-2023-34362",
        "CVE-2022-24086",
        "CVE-2021-3007"
    ] ;

    tools_used : [
        "SQLMap automated SQL injection detection and exploitation framework",
        "Burp Suite Pro active scanner for parameter injection discovery",
        "Havij (legacy) and DSSS for targeted manual-assisted injection",
        "Metasploit modules for known CVE SQL injection exploitation",
        "Custom PHP web shells (b374k, p0wny-shell) deployed via 
INTO OUTFILE or file-write post-exploitation"
    ] ;

    capec_id         : "CAPEC-66" ;
    kill_chain_phase : EXPLOITATION ;

    data_sources : [
        "Web application firewall logs for requests containing 
SQL injection pattern signatures including UNION, SELECT, 
information_schema, sleep(), benchmark(), WAITFOR DELAY, 
and hexadecimal encoding variants",
        "Database audit logs for unusual query patterns including 
information_schema queries, high-frequency UNION SELECT 
statements, and queries returning anomalously large result sets",
        "Web server access logs showing automated parameter fuzzing 
patterns: high request rate with varying parameter values 
from a single IP or IP range, sequential numeric parameter 
enumeration, and error-inducing payloads generating HTTP 500 responses",
        "File integrity monitoring alerts for new PHP files 
created in web root directories, particularly with 
obfuscated file content or eval()-based code execution patterns",
        "Database user privilege audit showing application 
account being used for FILE, EXECUTE, or CREATE operations"
    ] ;

    mitigations : [
        "M1051 - Update software: apply patches for all known 
SQL injection CVEs in e-commerce platform and plugin dependencies",
        "M1016 - Vulnerability scanning: conduct regular DAST 
scanning of all application input surfaces and API endpoints",
        "M1026 - Privileged account management: apply least-privilege 
database account permissions, denying FILE and DDL privileges",
        "M1050 - Exploit protection: deploy and tune WAF in 
enforcement mode with SQL injection signatures",
        "M1035 - Limit access to resource over network: restrict 
database server network accessibility to application servers only; 
deny direct internet routing to database port"
    ] ;

    platforms : [
        "Web Application",
        "Linux",
        "Windows"
    ] ;

    privilege_required : NONE ;
    impact_type        : DATA_THEFT ;

    notes : "SQL injection remains one of the most consistently 
exploited web application vulnerability classes despite being 
in the OWASP Top 10 for over 15 consecutive years and having 
a thoroughly understood and simple countermeasure (parameterisation). 
Its persistence is attributable to: legacy codebases with embedded 
string concatenation query patterns that are expensive to refactor; 
third-party plugins and themes with injection-vulnerable code that 
platform operators cannot directly control; developers bypassing 
ORM parameterisation when writing custom query logic for performance; 
and the long tail of small e-commerce operators without the security 
engineering resources to maintain secure development practices. 
The MOVEit CVE-2023-34362 exploitation demonstrates that SQL injection 
in enterprise file transfer middleware can be just as catastrophic 
as e-commerce platform injection, producing the largest breach event 
of 2023 by affected organisation count" ;
}
